Andrea Smith says the Charlotte Chamber of Commerce wants to be “the front door” to the city.

Smith, Bank of America’s (NYSE: BAC) chief administrative officer who is also currently chairing the chamber, spoke about the organization’s new mission Tuesday at Commercial Real Estate Women Charlotte’s March luncheon.

2017 Charlotte Chamber chair Andrea Smith cuts up with Bob Morgan, chamber president and CEO, at the organization's annual meeting in December.
Enlarge
2017 Charlotte Chamber chair Andrea Smith cuts up with Bob Morgan, chamber president and… more

NANCY PIERCE

The CBJ reported in January the chamber is broadening its mission to be more inclusive. Smith says it’s important to bring more voices to the table to better represent Charlotte’s business community.

“Gone are the days of the chamber being your grandfather’s chamber,” Smith says. “It’s really relevant to what’s going on today.”

Smith says the chamber has a new focus on innovation and entrepreneurship. The chamber created a new entrepreneur-in-residence role this year and is working to boost infrastructure and resources for startups.

Justin Gaither, founder of eCampus Ventures, is listed as the chamber’s entrepreneur in residence for 2017.

“That’s been a population we have gotten a lot of feedback from at the chamber that has felt under represented,” Smith says. “So we really want to bring those voices to the table and see what we can do to make the environment much more appealing to more entrepreneurs.”

Smith says the chamber has three pillars it is focused on now: Connect, innovate and grow.

“We want to be a chamber that helps connect people, helps connect people to nonprofits, helps connect businesses to people and connects the work that’s going on all around Charlotte,” Smith says. “We’re going to really foster an innovative environment.”

She says the chamber was too exclusive in the past. Smith hopes to give more people access to the chamber’s resources.

Smith also says the chamber is planning to bring in two people to replace Natalie English, who was the chamber’s public policy chief for many years. English left the chamber in January to lead Wilmington’s Chamber of Commerce.

“That position is going to be replaced with two people just to really focus on the public policy aspects and where the chamber can be helpful,” Smith says. “Again, bringing more voices to the table.”

