Software and hardware maker Oracle (ORCL)  is expected to report a year-over-year decrease in earnings but a gain in revenue for its fiscal 2017 third quarter after Wednesday's market close. Analysts will be looking at the company's SaaS and PaaS bookings, as well as its new software licenses. 

Analysts expect Oracle to report per-share earnings of 62 cents on revenue of $9.26 billion. The Redwood City, Calif.-based company posted earnings of 64 cents on revenue of $9.01 billion for the comparable period last year. This will be the first time Netsuite's full quarterly results are included in the report after Oracle acquired the cloud software company for $9.3 billion in November. 

During Oracle's 2017 second quarter conference call, founder Larry Ellison claimed that the company could book over $2 billion in annual cloud sales for the year. In addition, CEO Mark Hurd said, "Q3 has a chance to be our best quarter ever, period." 

The CEO's attempt to reassure investors came after the company's cloud bookings declined from $602 million in the 2016 fourth quarter to $272 million in the 2017 first quarter, before rising again to $377 million in the 2017 second quarter. In order to justify this seesaw in bookings, the company needs to report about $600 million in cloud business for the quarter, Davidson said in a note on Monday. "Given the steep implied sequential growth rates, success on this metric will likely dictate near-term stock performance," the firm said.

Jefferies said in a note on Monday that it's expecting the company to follow through on its claims by delivering stronger-than-expected cloud bookings. Drexel released a similarly upbeat note, saying "Oracle began pushing aggressively into the cloud, negatively impacting sales and EPS along the way; however, we believe the worst of this cloud transition is over and we expect Oracle will return to annual EPS growth in FY:18 for the first time since FY:14."

Pacific Crest Securities was less sure about Oracle's cloud business being a positive for the quarter. "Oracle is seeing acceleration in cloud, specifically in its SaaS and PaaS products, which is likely to create uncertainty and inconsistency in its model during this transition," the firm wrote in a note to investors this morning. "Therefore, despite a relatively attractive valuation, we see limited upside in ORCL from current levels."

Another key figure that analysts will be looking for is an improvement in new software licenses (also known as its "on premise" business) after the company reported a 19% year-over-year decline in this area for the 2017 second quarter. MKM Partners is expecting a 16% year-over-year decline for its license business this quarter. Some investors are concerned about risk for this segment in the fourth quarter as a result of management noting that cloud transition has the most dampening effect during the seasonally strong fourth quarter, according to the firm. 

"Looking out, relative improvement to license is key to ORCL as the bull case looks for the best EPS growth in years in FY18 (9%) behind a 12% decline in licenses vs. 16% in FY17," MKM Partners wrote. 

While Oracle is up about 11% year-to-date vs. the 6% rise in the S&P 500, Canaccord said that's mainly because "investors who missed the rally tend to prefer value." The firm claimed that it's "cautiously optimistic that Oracle can at least maintain operating and free cash flow margins despite spooling up a big push against Amazon  (AMZN) AWS. Even so, if we sense an adverse wiggle, the stock's rally could mean that we will downgrade ORCL from a BUY that we have maintained for 3+ years."

BMO Capital was similarly skeptical about the company, wanting to see more positive results from the company, according to a note released on Monday. The firm said that Oracle has missed Wall Street's estimates in seven of the past eight quarters by an average of about 1% and $100 million. "During this same period, software licenses have declined on average 10% CC and 14% on a reported basis," the firm wrote. "Hence, we think investor expectations remain relatively low. We believe ORCL needs to consistently meet (not beat) targets, including guidance and Street estimates, for the shares to move higher."

According to analyst ratings on FactSet, the company currently has 22 buy ratings, 12 hold ratings and 1 sell rating.

