Waitr Inc., a food delivery service that is partly managed out of Sacramento, has raised $10 million from a group of Gulf Coast investors led by New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees.

Brees owns a restaurant in New Orleans, the sports-themed Walk-On's Bistreaux & Bar, as well as multiple locations of Dunkin’ Donuts in Louisiana. His restaurant has been a customer of Waitr, which offers a smartphone app and website that connects restaurants and customers with its delivery service.

Kayleigh Locastro, a driver for food delivery service Waitr, picking up an order from OBO' Italian Table & Bar in Sacramento.
Enlarge
Kayleigh Locastro, a driver for food delivery service Waitr, picking up an order from… more

DENNIS MCCOY | SACRAMENTO BUSINESS JOURNAL

“I have seen firsthand how Waitr’s software platform can give a restaurant new revenue streams they might not have otherwise. We have seen the growth in our own restaurants after signing on with Waitr,” said Brees, in a news release.

Lake Charles, Louisiana-based Waitr last year bought Requested, a Sacramento-based company offering an app that handled restaurant payments, reservations and discounts. Some of Requested's Sacramento-based management team remained with the combined company after the acquisition. Sonny Mayugba, Requested's co-founder and CEO, is chief marketing officer with Waitr. He is also co-founder of The Red Rabbit Kitchen and Bar in midtown. Nichole "Coco" Barnum, Requested's other co-founder and chief operating officer, is head of product with Waitr.

The new investment will help Waitr grow into new markets, spokesman Dean Turcol said. The company now serves 18 cities and the investment will help it expand to 40 by the end of the year.

Locally, Waitr serves Roseville, Rocklin and started serving Sacramento last month.

The service charges a flat fee of $6.99 for food deliveries.

It is competing against other restaurant delivery services that have entered the Sacramento market in recent years, including San Francisco-based Postmates, DoorDash and Caviar, and Sacramento-based FoodJets.

