What do you do when your stock price triples in two weeks? Sell as many shares as you can, whereever you can sell them.

That seemed to be the strategy of the management at Aurinia Pharmaceuticals Inc. AUPH, +0.76% which saw its stock rocket from $3.56 at the end of February to $10.54 on Monday, amid positive results from studies of its treatment for lupus.

Late Monday, the company announced a public offering of common shares but didn’t specify how many shares it intended to sell, just saying the offering was “subject to market conditions.” The offering was made as part of a registration statement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission in November 2015.

Ahead of Tuesday’s open, the Canada-based company said it managed to sell 22.3 million common shares, which would effectively increase the number of shares outstanding by 42%. All shares were being sold by the company.

“Aurinia has achieve several important milestones over the past several months; this momentum led to an oversubscribed deal, a premium to the stock price 5 days ago and an overall shift of our shareholder base to long-term institutional shareholders,” the company said in an emailed statement to MarketWatch.

0:00 / 0:00
Need a raise? This FBI negotiator shows you how(1:25)
Chris Voss, former lead kidnapping negotiator for the FBI, knows how to get what he wants. In this episode of "Everyday Hostages," an original Moneyish series, Voss breaks down exactly how to negotiate a higher salary.

Aurinia’s shares plunged 25% in afternoon trade, on heavy volume of 38.7 million shares. The stock was the biggest percentage decliner and the second-most active on the Nasdaq exchange.

FactSet
Given the size of the offering, which was more than double the full-day average volume of 9.1 million shares, it is no wonder the underwriters of the offering couldn’t sell the shares at a price anywhere near Monday’s closing price.

Underwriters Leerink Partners LLC and Cantor Fitzgerald & Co. were able to price the offering at $6.75 a share, a 36% discount to Monday’s close of $10.54.

Despite the deep discount, the price was still nearly double what it was just two weeks ago. The company still expects to pocket about $150.5 million, before fees and commission. Aurinia plans to use those proceeds for research and development, including the funding of a phase 3 trial of its lupus treatment.

“We believe that the proceeds from the offering provides us with the ability to quickly bring to market an effective treatment for patients suffering from lupus nephritis by bringing voclosporin through phase 3 trials and associated regulatory filings and will also enable us to explore other potential indications for its use,” Aurinia told MarketWatch.

Aurinia’s stock has nearly quadrupled year to date, while the SPDR S&P Pharmaceuticals exchange-traded fund XPH, -0.91%  has climbed 5.6% and the S&P 500 index SPX, -0.34%  has gained 5.7%.

