Morgan Stanley analyst Rajeev Lalwani and team upgraded Boeing (BA) in June, noting at the time that everyone simply hated the stock. Since then, Boeing’s shares have gained 40%, so what’s an analyst to do? Downgrade its stock, of course.


Agence France-Presse/Getty Images
And that’s exactly what Lalwani and team did today. They cut Boeing’s shares to Equal Weight from Overwieght, not because they dislike the stock, as Barron’s Avi Salzman did when he panned the stock last May, but because everyone seems to recognize the potential of the company. They explain:

A risk-reward that now has more balance drives our shift to Equal-weight. Our thesis on BA was that the combination of poor sentiment, a slowing (but not rolling over) aero cycle, and robust FCF made shares compelling. With shares now up ~40% from the middle of last year and at an all-time high, the risks now appear more balanced. In addition, we believe it will be difficult for shares to move too far above a peer (or market) multiple, which is where they sit today (~18xvs. ~16.5x peers and ~17x market on 2018E EPS). Given that BA has the strongest cash flow profile in A&D per a 7-8% FCF yield (and growing) along with a half a trillion dollar backlog, we view the premium as justified and more than offsetting the cycle risks. And when assessing the risk-reward in shares, as observed in our bull-bear analysis and discussed further below, the upside and downside ranges from a balanced ~$120 to ~$250, thus supporting our move to Equal-weight.

Shares of Boeing have dipped 0.2% to $178.31 at 12:24 pm. today.

